Review this Go code and identify the concurrency bug:

var cache = map[string]string{}

func get(key string) string {
    return cache[key]
}

func set(key, value string) {
    cache[key] = value
}

completion:
**Data race**: The map is accessed concurrently without synchronisation. In Go, concurrent map reads and writes (or concurrent writes) cause a fatal runtime panic: `concurrent map read and map write`.

Fix with sync.RWMutex — reads can proceed concurrently, writes are exclusive:

```go
var (
    mu    sync.RWMutex
    cache = map[string]string{}
)

func get(key string) (string, bool) {
    mu.RLock()
    defer mu.RUnlock()
    v, ok := cache[key]
    return v, ok
}

func set(key, value string) {
    mu.Lock()
    defer mu.Unlock()
    cache[key] = value
}
```

Alternatively use `sync.Map` if the access pattern is mostly reads with infrequent writes, or if keys are written once and read many times.

